            <para>The following procedure can be performed without removing the freon compressor.</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen the freon compressor drive belt.
                    <emph type="bold">DO NOT REMOVE BELT.</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove (Items 1 through 7,
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9216021">Figure 1</hotlnk>) which make up the old style freon compressor base
                    mounting. Save the four 3/8 x 1 inch hex hd. bolts (Item 8,
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9216021">Figure 1</hotlnk>); they will be reused.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <para>Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f9216022">Figure 2</hotlnk>
                and the
                <hotlnk xrefid="t9216021">Parts List</hotlnk>
                for all item numbers in parentheses.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fasten the lower mounting bracket (Item 12) to the front timing gear housing with two
                    hex hd. bolts (Item 13), two 1/2 inch flat washers (Item 16), two 1/2 inch lock washers (Item 17),
                    and two hex nuts (Item 14). Tighten finger tight.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fasten the upper mounting bracket (Item 1) to the lower mounting bracket (Item 12) with
                    hex hd. bolt (Item 7), bushing (Item 6) and upper mounting brace (Item 2) as illustrated in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9216022">Figure 2</hotlnk>. Secure with flat washer (Item 16), lock washer (Item
                    17) and 1/2 inch hex nut (Item 18). Tighten hand tight.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fasten the freon compressor to the upper mounting bracket (Item 1) with the four 3/8 x 1
                    inch bolts removed in step 2. Tighten finger tight.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fasten the upper mounting brace (Item 2) to the engine as illustrated in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9216022">Figure 2</hotlnk>with hex bolt (Item 3), flat washer (Item 4) and lock
                    washer (Item 5). Tighten hand tight.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install lower mounting brace (Item 8) to the engine with a hex hd. bolt (Item 9) and to
                    the lower mounting bracket (Item 12) with hex hd. bolt (Item 10) and hex nut (Item 11).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten all fasteners except bolt (Item 7) and nut (Item 18) that secures the upper
                    mounting bracket (Item 1) to the lower mounting bracket (Item 12). Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="x9216022">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tension belt. Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="x9216021">BELT TENSION</hotlnk>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten bolt (Item 7) and nut (Item 18) that secures the upper mounting bracket (Item 1)
                    to the lower mounting bracket (Item 12). Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="x9216022">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
        <svcproc id="x9216021" svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="0">
            <title>BELT TENSION</title>
            <para>When replacing the belt, the belt tension should be set at 130 lbs.
                <emph type="bold">COLD.</emph>
                The use of a belt tension gauge is mandatory. After 15 to 30 minutes run-in, check belt tension. The
                belt tension should remain at 100 lbs. or greater. Re-tension if necessary. After 1000 miles, recheck
                and adjust the belt tension. The vehicle should then operate to normal maintenance intervals for belt
                check and tension. Any misalignment should be corrected at the time of belt installation.
            </para>
        </svcproc>
